courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students are expected to get a basic understanding of:

1. The origin and development of major artistic traditions in China;

2. The artistic and cultural significance of Chinese art;

3. The achievements and contributions of great masters;

4. The ways of looking at Chinese art; and

5. The relationship between Chinese art and foreign culture.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. The art and culture of prehistoric and Bronze Age China;

2. Chinese ceramics and other decorative arts;

3. Chinese imperial art throughout the ages;

4. Art of the Chinese literati;

5. Chinese religious art; and

6. Artistic exchange between China and its neighboring countries.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Students taking this course will:

* acquire basic anthropological knowledge in multiculturalism, globalization, and ethnicity and develop the ability to comprehend and apply related knowledge;
* gain a better appreciation of Chinese cultural heritage and other cultural traditions;
* recognize that Chinese culture involves multicultural components;
* acquire a critical mind to examine any social issues; and
* recognize the importance of sustainable development from the social and cultural perspectives.

Student should be able to:
1 Distinguish different genres of Chinese music, and identify their essential features;
2 Recognize the role of music in Chinese culture, and its relations to other aspects of Chinese culture;
3 Outline the circumstantial factors that have affected the development of Chinese music;
4 Conduct an informed discussion of a wide range of issues concerning Chinese music.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

A) understand the basic ideas about Chinese religious culture and concepts;

B) identify the essential characteristics and development of Chinese political traditions;

C) critically analyse the issues regarding Chinese political traditions and religious culture.

Upon the completion of the course, students will be able to –

1. recognize the rich history of Chinese constitution and legal culture;
2. understand the relevance of Chinese history and civilization to our understanding the laws of China;
3. identity the major achievements of the *Zhonghua Faxi* in history;
4. recognize the inherent connection of China’s ancient constitution to the overarching goal of the unitary Chinese state;
5. gain deeper understanding of constitutional reform and legal modernization in China in the early 20th century;
6. achieve in-depth understanding of the continuity and innovation of China’s constitution and legal culture since the start of reform and opening-up in the late 20th century;
7. understand the rising importance of the Constitution in shaping the new culture of Chinese in the 21st century.

Upon the completion of the course, students will be able to

a) describe the characteristics of China’s foreign policies, its basic principles of foreign diplomacy, and the content of some major policy initiatives of contemporary China such as the Belt-and-Road Initiative;

b) recognize the influence of ancient Chinese philosophical thought on contemporary China’s foreign policies, with regard to key concepts such as authority, hegemony, and *tianxia*;

c) analyze some major issues and challenges in China’s relations with the major powers in the world, in particular the US and Russia, in the context of the history of these relations and contemporary global context;

d) analyze some major issues and challenges in China’s relations with the global south, in particular the countries of Asia and Africa, in the context of the historical legacies of these relations and contemporary geopolitics;

e) approach general issues in contemporary China’s foreign relations from some theoretical frameworks, drawing on Chinese and foreign scholarship and with an informed historical understanding.

Upon the completion of the course, students will be able to –

1. recognise the main intellectual foundations that have shaped the people, culture, and society in the Chinese civilisation;
2. identify the key historical currents that forged and defined China’s transformations;
3. describe the core characteristics of China’s pathways towards modernity and modernisation;
4. understand the major economic transformations in modern China and the challenges it faces in the context of global economy;
5. understand the development of science and technology in China from the perspectives of cultural, societal and institutional change;
6. achieve a deeper understanding of the role of China’s tradition in shaping modern and contemporary China;
7. approach selected issues pertaining to China’s past and present from multidisciplinary perspectives;
8. gain a deepened appreciation of the grandeur and complexity of China.

courses.course_syllabus:
The syllabus of this course comprises of four main areas of instruction:

(1) Theories of modernization and social change pertaining to the study of Chinese society;

(2) Aspects of cultural changes as in the way of life, the social psychology, and the religious beliefs of the Chinese people;

(3) Aspects of institutional transformation as in the family, the state, and the economic system;

(4) Aspects of social structural changes as in modes of social stratification and modes of production.

While the first area sets the theoretical direction of the course as a whole, the other three areas address matters of more topical concerns.In each case, however, the discussion will focus upon the variegated trajectories that led “from tradition to modernity”.
